			&lt;div class=&quot;eight columns&quot;&gt;
				&lt;a name=&quot;nesting&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
				&lt;h3&gt;
					Nesting Support&lt;/h3&gt;
			&lt;/div&gt;
			&lt;div class=&quot;four columns tabs&quot;&gt;
				&lt;dl class=&quot;tabs pill small&quot;&gt;
					&lt;dd class=&quot;active&quot;&gt;
						&lt;a href=&quot;#nestingBasics&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/dd&gt;
					&lt;dd&gt;
						&lt;a href=&quot;#nestingCode&quot;&gt;Code&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/dd&gt;
				&lt;/dl&gt;
			&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;ul class=&quot;tabs-content&quot;&gt;
			&lt;li class=&quot;active&quot; id=&quot;nestingBasicsTab&quot;&gt;
				&lt;p&gt;
					The grid allows for nesting down as far as you&#039;d like, though at a certain point it will get absurd. You can use this nesting to create quite complex layouts, as well as some other tricks like form layouts or visual elements.&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;div class=&quot;row display&quot;&gt;
					&lt;div class=&quot;twelve columns&quot;&gt;
						.twelve
						&lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
