		&lt;div class=&quot;row tabs&quot;&gt;
			&lt;div class=&quot;eight columns&quot;&gt;
				&lt;a name=&quot;mobile-grid&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
				&lt;h3&gt;
					Mobile Grid&lt;/h3&gt;
			&lt;/div&gt;
			&lt;div class=&quot;four columns tabs&quot;&gt;
				&lt;dl class=&quot;tabs pill small&quot;&gt;
					&lt;dd class=&quot;active&quot;&gt;
						&lt;a href=&quot;#mobileEx&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/dd&gt;
					&lt;dd&gt;
						&lt;a href=&quot;#mobileCode&quot;&gt;Code&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/dd&gt;
				&lt;/dl&gt;
			&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;
			The grid has two modes of adapting for small displays like phones. The first requires no work at all â€” the grid will linearize on a small device so your columns stack vertically. This is useful to quickly adapt a desktop layout to a simple scrolling mobile layout. When you&#039;re creating your layout you can optionally attach classes that take your existing grid elements and attach them to a four column phone grid.&lt;/p&gt;
